{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67e34b57-2c4d-48c1-aadb-96346b0d1b9d","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n## Error 1: `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators\n\nC# 15 now rejects `&&`/`||` when the left operand's compile-time type is an **interface** declaring `operator true`/`operator false` and the other operand is `dynamic`. The runtime dynamic binder cannot dispatch **static virtual interface members**, so the compiler now correctly rejects this at compile time (previously it would compile but fail or misbehave at runtime).\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Cast `right` to a concrete type: `left && (CompositeFilter)right`\n- Use non-short-circuit `&` if short-circuiting isn't needed\n- Avoid `dynamic` entirely with explicit typing\n\n## Error 2: CS0518 with `ref readonly` lambda\n\nCS0518 (\"Predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler's lowering of `ref readonly` return lambdas now requires a new well-known BCL type that your project doesn't reference. C# 15 changed the internal representation for ref-returning delegates.\n\n**Fix:** Ensure your project targets `net11.0` **and** your SDK is fully updated (`dotnet sdk check`). If you're multi-targeting or using an older `Microsoft.NETCore.App` ref pack, update all framework references. A `dotnet workload update` may also be needed to sync the SDK components.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f4d5cc24-9849-4231-9a37-a77a90314194","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze each one:\n\n**Error 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler handles short-circuit logical operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe issue here is that `&&` is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve the operators at compile time for the non-dynamic operand. \n\n\nIn C# 15, the compiler now requires that `operator true`/`operator false` be resolvable at compile time in a way that's compatible with dynamic binding, whereas earlier versions would defer this resolution to runtime. The problem is specifically that interfaces can now define `static` operators like `operator true`, but the compiler's handling of these with dynamic operands has changed, causing the short-circuit evaluation to fail. The `&&` operator isn't directly overloadable—instead it's desugared to use `operator false` for short-circuiting and `operator &` for the actual operation. When the left operand is an `IFilter` interface with static virtual operators and the right is `dynamic`, C# 15 likely rejects this because the dynamic binder can't resolve interface static virtual members at runtime, breaking the short-circuit logic.\n\nNow looking at the second error in `RefHelper.cs` involving a `ref readonly` lambda...\n\nStill writing lambda code... on known compiler evolution patterns. The first error likely stems from C# 15 rejecting the combination of `&&`/`||` operators with dynamic types when the left operand defines `operator true`/`operator false` as static interface members, since the dynamic binder can't dispatch to static virtual members. I'd need to either cast to a concrete type, use non-short-circuit `&` instead, or avoid mixing interface static operators with dynamic altogether.\n\nFor the second error with the ref readonly lambda, CS0518 suggests a missing predefined type reference—\n\nC# 15 probably changed how ref readonly lambdas are lowered to require a new BCL type or attribute that isn't available in the current SDK. There's also a potential mismatch in the lambda where the return is declared `ref readonly int` but the body uses `ref value` instead of `ref readonly value`, which could trigger stricter validation in the new version. the compiler might need `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` from .NET 8, or C# 15 could have introduced a new attribute requirement that's missing from your project references. For the second error, I'm realizing the issue might be a type mismatch—the lambda is trying to return `ref readonly int`, but the actual return value is `ref int` (mutable), which isn't compatible. The second error is likely a new validation in C# 15 that prevents `&&` operators from working with `dynamic` operands when the left side is an interface with `operator true`/`operator false` declarations, since the runtime can't properly dispatch static virtual interface members. The third error suggests C# 15 introduced a new internal type for representing `ref readonly` return lambdas that isn't available in the current SDK or framework version, so updating to the latest .NET runtime libraries should resolve it.","outputTokens":2601,"requestId":"0409:20BD61:6FBDFE:807572:6A052A76"},"id":"9e2fa83a-12f3-45ad-a2ac-8aea8e2e064a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:51:40.202Z","parentId":"41b63211-31e6-421b-b389-5146b326a516"}
